tasks.taskText:
Let's start by creating a simple program that prints “Hello World” to the screen.@class MyClass {
  public static void main(String[ ] args) {
     System.out.println("Hello World");
   }
}@In Java, every line of code that can actually run needs to be inside a class.
In our example, we named the class MyClass. You will learn more about classes in the upcoming modules.

In Java, each application has an entry point, or a starting point, which is a method called main. Along with main, the keywords public and static will also be explained later.@As a summary:
- Every program in Java must have a class.
- Every Java program starts from the main method.

Next is the body of the main method, enclosed in curly braces:@  {
      System.out.println("Hello World!");
  }@The println method prints a line of text to the screen.
The System class and its out stream are used to access the println method.@In classes, methods, and other flow-control structures code is always enclosed in curly braces { }.

You can pass a different text as the parameter to the println method to print it.@class MyClass {
   public static void main(String[ ] args) {
      System.out.println("I am learning Java");
   }}@In Java, each code statement must end with a semicolon. @Remember: do not use semicolons after method and class declarations that follow with the body defined using the curly braces.
